      PRPLS
   =20
 =20

There are two ways for companies to hold elections for their boards of dire=
ctors. The normal way is that the company has, say, seven board seats, and =
each shareholder gets to vote for up to seven directors, and each share=C2=
=A0voted=C2=A0for a candidate counts as one vote,=C2=A0and whichever seven =
candidates get the most votes win. Most of the time, the company nominates =
seven people, they are the only choices, and the shareholders just vote for=
 them.=C2=A0But sometimes there will be a contested election: An activist s=
hareholder will nominate candidates (perhaps seven, perhaps fewer) and run =
a proxy fight to try to get shareholders to vote for her candidates, and th=
e shareholders will end up electing either the company=E2=80=99s candidates=
 or the activist=E2=80=99s or, occasionally, a mix of the two slates.
The other way =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is called =E2=80=9Ccumulative=E2=80=9D voti=
ng =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that each shareholder gets seven votes per share, but =
can assign them to whichever candidate or candidates she wants. She can vot=
e all seven votes for one candidate, if she wants, or four for one and thre=
e for another, or one each for seven candidates, or whatever. And then whic=
hever candidate gets the most total votes wins.
This is, generally, good for activists.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CCumulative voting is =
a type of voting system that helps strengthen the ability of minority share=
holders to elect a director,=E2=80=9D  says the US Securities and Exchange =
Commission. With normal voting, if the company and an activist each nominat=
e seven candidates, and if 30% of shareholders vote with the activist and 7=
0% vote with management, then all of management=E2=80=99s directors will be=
 elected. With cumulative voting, though, if 30% of shareholders split thei=
r seven votes among just two of the activist=E2=80=99s candidates, then bot=
h of those candidates will be elected (each with 15% of the vote), and they=
 will join the board (along with five of the management nominees).
Companies=E2=80=99 boards and managers mostly do not want this, for obvious=
 reasons: Companies want to be able to pick a full board of people who are =
on the same page and want to work together, rather than having a couple of =
interlopers in the boardroom who were chosen by a disgruntled minority of s=
hareholders.=C2=A0Delaware law says that a company=E2=80=99s certificate of=
 incorporation may provide for cumulative voting, but it is not the default=
, and in fact it is quite rare among US public companies.
Purple Innovation Inc. is a publicly traded mattress company that went publ=
ic through a special purpose acquisition company in 2018. One=C2=A0big shar=
eholder, Coliseum Capital Management LLC,=C2=A0owns about 45% of its stock.=
 Last September, Coliseum  offered to acquire the rest of Purple for $4.35 =
per share; the stock had been trading at around $3. A special committee of =
Purple=E2=80=99s board of directors  declined the  offer; the stock closed =
yesterday at $4.63.
On Monday,=C2=A0Coliseum announced that it was nominating five candidates t=
o Purple=E2=80=99s seven-member board of directors. (One of them is Coliseu=
m=E2=80=99s managing partner, who is already on Purple=E2=80=99s board.)=C2=
=A0With 45% of the stock, Coliseum can probably elect all the directors it =
likes.
  [1]
 Once it controls the board =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I guess it could=C2=A0try to for=
ce through an acquisition, though that is hard and it has said it won=E2=80=
=99t. In its announcement, Coliseum =E2=80=9Cconfirmed that it is no longer=
 pursuing its September 2022 proposal to acquire the remaining shares not o=
wned by Coliseum=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccommitted that if it does make a sim=
ilar proposal in the future, it will be conditioned on the same terms as th=
e September 2022 proposal: it must be approved by a special committee of Pu=
rple=E2=80=99s board and by the holders of a majority of the stock not then=
 owned by Coliseum.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Purple=E2=80=99s management was not thrilled, and=C2=A0its special committe=
e  put out a statement:

We are extremely disappointed that Coliseum has launched a proxy fight seek=
ing to replace a majority of Purple=E2=80=99s Board, which currently compri=
ses seven members.
Coliseum=E2=80=99s Managing Partner Adam Gray has served on Purple=E2=80=99=
s Board of Directors since the time the Company went public in 2018. He has=
 been the Chairman of the Board=E2=80=99s Nomination & Governance Committee=
 (N&G Committee) since its formation. During this time, Mr. Gray has been a=
 fully engaged director, regularly contributing to Board composition and ma=
nagement succession planning, developing long-term growth strategies, and d=
etermining the appropriate capital structure to support the Company=E2=80=
=99s promising future.
At no time did Mr. Gray express his discontent with the way the business is=
 being managed or the Company=E2=80=99s strategic direction. He appears con=
tent with management, and he has been the director most responsible for the=
 Board=E2=80=99s composition, given his role as Chairman of the N&G Committ=
ee. Mr. Gray=E2=80=99s posture only changed in January when the Company rej=
ected Coliseum Capital=E2=80=99s undervalued buyout proposal of $4.35 per s=
hare.=C2=A0

But there is not a whole=C2=A0ton=C2=A0that the board can do, given that Co=
liseum owns 45% of the stock.=C2=A0
One thing that you might think, if you were Purple=E2=80=99s current direct=
ors, is something like =E2=80=9Cboy, I wish we had cumulative voting.=E2=80=
=9D If Purple had cumulative voting, then the non-Coliseum shareholders who=
 don=E2=80=99t want Coliseum to take over the board could band together and=
 elect, you know, two or three or even possibly four directors. (Non-Colise=
um holders have 55% of the votes, though they are more dispersed than Colis=
eum and so less likely to vote all together even if they mostly=C2=A0do=C2=
=A0agree with management.) But  Purple=E2=80=99s corporate charter does=C2=
=A0not provide for cumulative voting; changing that would require a shareho=
lder vote, which doesn=E2=80=99t really work.=C2=A0
But Purple=E2=80=99s charter does allow for what is called =E2=80=9Cblank-c=
heck preferred stock=E2=80=9D: The board can issue shares of preferred stoc=
k with any terms that it wants, including any=C2=A0voting=C2=A0rights that =
it wants. We have   talked about this sort of thing recently in the context=
 of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.: AMC was having trouble getting shareho=
lder approval to issue more stock, so it issued a new class of preferred st=
ock (called APEs) that had voting rights, and placed that stock in friendly=
 hands to make shareholder approval more likely. Issuing new common stock w=
ould have required shareholder approval that AMC couldn=E2=80=99t get, but =
issuing new preferred stock that=C2=A0looked=C2=A0and=C2=A0voted=C2=A0like =
common stock was easy.
Purple had a similar idea, and yesterday it issued  this press release:

Purple Innovation, Inc. (NASDAQ: PRPL) ("Purple" or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=
=80=9D), a comfort innovation company known for creating the "World's First=
 No Pressure=C2=AE Mattress," today announced that the Special Committee of=
 its Board of Directors (the =E2=80=9CBoard=E2=80=9D) has declared a divide=
nd of one new Proportional Representation Preferred Linked Stock (=E2=80=9C=
PRPLS=E2=80=9D) for each 100 shares of Purple common stock (=E2=80=9CCommon=
 Stock=E2=80=9D) owned by Purple=E2=80=99s shareholders. Each PRPLS will vo=
te together with the Common Stock in the election of directors, and related=
 matters, and carry 10,000 votes each.
Holders of PRPLS will be entitled to allocate their votes among the nominee=
s in director elections on a cumulative basis. PRPLS holders can allocate a=
ll, none, or a portion of their votes to each director nominee up for elect=
ion at the Company=E2=80=99s meetings of shareholders. As an example, share=
holders who collectively own 30% of Purple=E2=80=99s Common Stock will be a=
ble to use the voting rights associated with their PRPLS to effectively ele=
ct approximately 30% of the members of the Board.
=E2=80=9CThe purpose of the PRPLS is to protect all shareholders and treat =
them equally,=E2=80=9D said Paul J. Zepf, Purple Innovation=E2=80=99s Chair=
man of the Board. =E2=80=9CPurple shareholders will have the opportunity fo=
r proportional representation on the Purple Board of Directors. By cumulati=
ng their PRPLS votes for certain director nominees, public shareholders can=
 support the election of directors they believe will act independently to r=
epresent the interests of all shareholders in the boardroom, roughly in pro=
portion to their collective ownership in the Company.=E2=80=9D ...
Prior to the issuance of the PRPLS, Coliseum might have been able to single=
-handedly nominate and elect all of the directors on the Board, including t=
he five nominees Coliseum has selected.
With the issuance of PRPLS, all shareholders, including those not affiliate=
d with Coliseum, will be able to cumulate their PRPLS votes on director can=
didates they feel will best represent the interests of all shareholders. Th=
is will help ensure that all shareholders receive ongoing independent repre=
sentation on the Board. The PRPLS enable shareholders who are not affiliate=
d with Coliseum to choose and elect as many as 55% of the directors on the =
Purple Board.
The Company is issuing one-one hundredth PRPLS for each share of Common Sto=
ck held as of the close of business on February 24, 2023. The PRPLS will tr=
ade with the Common Stock and any new issuance of Common Stock will automat=
ically include a proportionate number of PRPLS. The PRPLS are redeemable at=
 any time by an affirmative vote of two-thirds of the members of the Board.

Ten thousand votes per PRPLS! I mean, each common share gets 1/100th of a P=
RPLS,
  [2]
 so each common share gets 100 extra votes. The one normal vote per common =
share is not cumulative, but the 100 PRPLS votes are, so Purple has effecti=
vely switched to cumulative voting.
I dunno, seems fine? A lot of the time, when companies try to fight off a b=
ig shareholder, they do it with things that=C2=A0discriminate=C2=A0against =
that shareholder: most classically a   poison pill (basically threatening t=
o give a ton of new stock to every shareholder except the one you don=E2=80=
=99t like), though there is also the time that CBS Corp.=E2=80=99s board of=
 directors tried to   issue a bunch of new stock to take away the super-vot=
ing rights of Shari Redstone, its controlling shareholder. Here, every shar=
eholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0Coliseum and otherwise =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets the same =
PRPLS and the same voting rights, but the board has changed how the votes g=
et counted.
Mostly we just live in a golden age of blank-check preferred stock with wei=
rd voting rights and fun acronyms. I don=E2=80=99t think that a lot of comp=
anies will=C2=A0copy=C2=A0this idea, just because you need a really specifi=
c set of circumstances (pretty much: a single shareholder with more than ab=
out 35% of the stock and less than 50%, whom the board doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0like) for this to make any sense. But if anyone does, will they use Purp=
le=E2=80=99s PRPLS name? As a little tribute? Or will they have to come up =
with their own acronym?

