   =20
      Crypto taxes
   =20
 =20

The basic proposition of crypto shadow banks like Celsius Network Ltd. was:
=09You deposit your crypto with Celsius.=09Celsius pays you some very high =
interest rate on your crypto,   as much as 18%, and uses your crypto to mak=
e risky bets.=09Celsius loses the money, can=E2=80=99t give you back your c=
rypto, and goes bankrupt.

I mean, that is not literally the proposition that Celsius advertised, but =
(1) it=E2=80=99s what happened and (2) it's=C2=A0kind of=C2=A0what it adver=
tised? Like, if you are financially literate, an 18% interest rate on a dem=
and deposit account does=C2=A0mean=C2=A0that they=E2=80=99re going to lose =
your money?=C2=A0=E2=80=9CEither the bank is lying or Celsius is lying,=E2=
=80=9D Celsius promoter Alex Mashinsky   famously said, so you had a 50/50 =
shot of getting it right.
Anyway, there is an obvious problem with this proposition, which is that Ce=
lsius loses your money and you don=E2=80=99t get it back. But there is also=
 another, slightly less obvious problem, which is that Celsius pays you 18%=
 interest. The problem is that=C2=A0you owe taxes on that interest, which y=
ou can=E2=80=99t pay, because Celsius lost your money. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s =
  Claire Ballentine reports:

Interest earned on bank accounts, certificates of deposit and corporate bon=
ds is subject to income tax in the year it=E2=80=99s generated, according t=
o the Internal Revenue Service. Typically, that=E2=80=99s a fairly straight=
forward process: Banks and other institutions send out 1099 forms listing t=
he taxpayer=E2=80=99s interest income, which is then used when determining =
overall obligations for tax season. =C2=A0
But in a quirk of last year=E2=80=99s crypto collapse, investors are now re=
ceiving tax bills for money locked up on platforms like Celsius and Voyager=
 Digital, which have frozen customer withdrawals as they undergo bankruptcy=
 proceedings.
It could hardly come at a worse time for crypto investors. Not only have di=
gital asset prices plunged in the wake of FTX=E2=80=99s collapse, but infla=
tion, high housing costs and rising interest rates are also making it more =
difficult for everyday people to afford regular expenses =E2=80=94 let alon=
e taxes on investments they=E2=80=99ve likely lost.=C2=A0

Paying 18% interest into your account, and then not letting you withdraw th=
e money from the account, ends up giving you negative cash flow; you=E2=80=
=99d have been better off without the interest.=C2=A0In=20
other Celsius news:

Celsius Network Ltd=C2=A0has proposed a plan that calls for most users to r=
ecover the majority of their assets and allows=C2=A0NovaWulf Digital Manage=
ment=C2=A0to manage a restructured version of the bankrupt crypto lender.
The proposal calls for Celsius users with less than $5,000 of crypto tied u=
p in interest-bearing accounts to receive a 70% recovery in the form of liq=
uid digital assets like Bitcoin and Ethereum,=C2=A0court papers=C2=A0show. =
Those smaller accounts make up most of Celsius=E2=80=99s interest-bearing a=
ccount holders.=C2=A0
Bigger account holders will receive tokenized shares of post-bankruptcy Cel=
sius and an unspecified amount of crypto, court papers show. The reborn com=
pany =E2=80=94 which will hold its crypto mining and illiquid assets =E2=80=
=94 =C2=A0will be managed by NovaWulf. =C2=A0
NovaWulf would inject as much as $55 million into the new company under the=
 plan, according to court papers. Its incentives will be =E2=80=9Cclosely a=
ligned=E2=80=9D with shareholders because of a profit-sharing arrangement, =
Celsius advisers said in a slide deck. =E2=80=A6
The plan also calls for Celsius users to reap any benefits of a trust that =
will sue former Celsius insiders, according to court papers.

Huge   growth area in crypto, really, tokenizing the right to sue the peopl=
e who made money in the last crypto boom.

