<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PRPLS</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two ways for companies to hold elect=
ions for their boards of directors. The normal way is that the company has,=
 say, seven board seats, and each shareholder gets to vote for up to seven =
directors, and each share=C2=A0voted=C2=A0for a candidate counts as one vot=
e,=C2=A0and whichever seven candidates get the most votes win. Most of the =
time, the company nominates seven people, they are the only choices, and th=
e shareholders just vote for them.=C2=A0But sometimes there will be a conte=
sted election: An activist shareholder will nominate candidates (perhaps se=
ven, perhaps fewer) and run a proxy fight to try to get shareholders to vot=
e for her candidates, and the shareholders will end up electing either the =
company=E2=80=99s candidates or the activist=E2=80=99s or, occasionally, a =
mix of the two slates.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other way =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is called =E2=
=80=9Ccumulative=E2=80=9D voting =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that each shareholder ge=
ts seven votes per share, but can assign them to whichever candidate or can=
didates she wants. She can vote all seven votes for one candidate, if she w=
ants, or four for one and three for another, or one each for seven candidat=
es, or whatever. And then whichever candidate gets the most total votes win=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, generally, good for activists.=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9CCumulative voting is a type of voting system that helps strengthen=
 the ability of minority shareholders to elect a director,=E2=80=9D <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuaW52ZXN0b3IuZ292L2ludHJvZHVjdGlvbi1pbnZlc3RpbmcvaW52ZXN0aW5nLWJhc2lj=
cy9nbG9zc2FyeS9jdW11bGF0aXZlLXZvdGluZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62d12f30" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> says the US Securities and Exchange Commission</a>. With normal vot=
ing, if the company and an activist each nominate seven candidates, and if =
30% of shareholders vote with the activist and 70% vote with management, th=
en all of management=E2=80=99s directors will be elected. With cumulative v=
oting, though, if 30% of shareholders split their seven votes among just tw=
o of the activist=E2=80=99s candidates, then both of those candidates will =
be elected (each with 15% of the vote), and they will join the board (along=
 with five of the management nominees).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Companies=E2=80=99 boards and managers mostly =
do not want this, for obvious reasons: Companies want to be able to pick a =
full board of people who are on the same page and want to work together, ra=
ther than having a couple of interlopers in the boardroom who were chosen b=
y a disgruntled minority of shareholders.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWxjb2RlLmRlbGF3YX=
JlLmdvdi90aXRsZTgvYzAwMS9zYzA3L2luZGV4Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2214=
2e9b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">Delaware law</a> says that a company=E2=80=99s certificate of=
 incorporation may provide for cumulative voting, but it is not the default=
, and in fact it is quite rare among US public companies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purple Innovation Inc. is a publicly traded ma=
ttress company that went public through a special purpose acquisition compa=
ny in 2018. One=C2=A0big shareholder, Coliseum Capital Management LLC,=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDk3NTEvMDAwMTE5Mz=
EyNTIzMDM3Mzk4L2Q0MzI5NjJkc2MxM2RhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3fa53ef0"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">owns about 45%</a> of its stock. Last September, Coliseum <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDk3NTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMjQ2=
Njk2L2Q0MDQ0NTRkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2225c1b0" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> of=
fered to acquire</a> the rest of Purple for $4.35 per share; the stock had =
been trading at around $3. A special committee of Purple=E2=80=99s board of=
 directors <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3056243=
0.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMD=
AwMTIxMzkwMDIzMDAzNTk4L2VhMTcxODk5ZXg5OS0xX3B1cnBsZWlubm92Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBcc8f5c2e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> declined</a> the <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDk3NTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIzMDA5NTYxL2Q0MzI0MThkZ=
Xg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB20780d91" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> offer</a>; the stoc=
k closed yesterday at $4.63.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Monday,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNo=
aXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDk3NTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIzMDM0NDUwL2Q0MjAxNTVkZXg5OTE=
uaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB60f29a19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Coliseum announced</a> t=
hat it was nominating five candidates to Purple=E2=80=99s seven-member boar=
d of directors. (One of them is Coliseum=E2=80=99s managing partner, who is=
 already on Purple=E2=80=99s board.)=C2=A0With 45% of the stock, Coliseum c=
an probably elect all the directors it likes.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Once it controls the board =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I guess it <em>could=C2=A0</=
em>try to force through an acquisition, though that is hard and it has said=
 it won=E2=80=99t. In its announcement, Coliseum =E2=80=9Cconfirmed that it=
 is no longer pursuing its September 2022 proposal to acquire the remaining=
 shares not owned by Coliseum=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccommitted that if it do=
es make a similar proposal in the future, it will be conditioned on the sam=
e terms as the September 2022 proposal: it must be approved by a special co=
mmittee of Purple=E2=80=99s board and by the holders of a majority of the s=
tock not then owned by Coliseum.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purple=E2=80=99s management was not thrilled, =
and=C2=A0its special committee <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci=
9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDIzMDEwOTc1L2VhMTczNDQ5LWRlZmExNGFfcHVycGxlL=
mh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf601e26c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> put out a statement</a>=
:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We are extremely disappointed that Coliseum ha=
s launched a proxy fight seeking to replace a majority of Purple=E2=80=99s =
Board, which currently comprises seven members.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coliseum=E2=80=99s Managing Partner Adam Gray =
has served on Purple=E2=80=99s Board of Directors since the time the Compan=
y went public in 2018. He has been the Chairman of the Board=E2=80=99s Nomi=
nation &amp; Governance Committee (N&amp;G Committee) since its formation. =
During this time, Mr. Gray has been a fully engaged director, regularly con=
tributing to Board composition and management succession planning, developi=
ng long-term growth strategies, and determining the appropriate capital str=
ucture to support the Company=E2=80=99s promising future.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At no time did Mr. Gray express his discontent=
 with the way the business is being managed or the Company=E2=80=99s strate=
gic direction. He appears content with management, and he has been the dire=
ctor most responsible for the Board=E2=80=99s composition, given his role a=
s Chairman of the N&amp;G Committee. Mr. Gray=E2=80=99s posture only change=
d in January when the Company rejected Coliseum Capital=E2=80=99s undervalu=
ed buyout proposal of $4.35 per share.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is not a whole=C2=A0<em>ton=C2=A0</e=
m>that the board can do, given that Coliseum owns 45% of the stock.=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that you might think, if you were Pu=
rple=E2=80=99s current directors, is something like =E2=80=9Cboy, I wish we=
 had cumulative voting.=E2=80=9D If Purple had cumulative voting, then the =
non-Coliseum shareholders who don=E2=80=99t want Coliseum to take over the =
board could band together and elect, you know, two or three or even possibl=
y four directors. (Non-Coliseum holders have 55% of the votes, though they =
are more dispersed than Coliseum and so less likely to vote all together ev=
en if they mostly=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>agree with management.) But <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDE5MDIy=
MTM4L2YxMHEwOTE5ZXgzLTFfcHVycGxlLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5c462dc" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> Purple=E2=80=99s corporate charter</a> does=C2=A0<em>not </em>provi=
de for cumulative voting; changing that would require a shareholder vote, w=
hich doesn=E2=80=99t really work.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Purple=E2=80=99s charter does allow for wh=
at is called =E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred stock=E2=80=9D: The board can i=
ssue shares of preferred stock with any terms that it wants, including any=
=C2=A0<em>voting=C2=A0</em>rights that it wants. We have <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDEvYW1jLWhhcy1zb21lLWNsZXZ=
lci1hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3=
NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIxNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZ=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6513909f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about this sort of th=
ing</a> recently in the context of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.: AMC was=
 having trouble getting shareholder approval to issue more stock, so it iss=
ued a new class of preferred stock (called APEs) that had voting rights, an=
d placed that stock in friendly hands to make shareholder approval more lik=
ely. Issuing new common stock would have required shareholder approval that=
 AMC couldn=E2=80=99t get, but issuing new preferred stock that=C2=A0<em>lo=
oked=C2=A0</em>and=C2=A0<em>voted=C2=A0</em>like common stock was easy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purple had a similar idea, and yesterday it is=
sued <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.2798=
53/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2NDM5NTMvMDAwMTIx=
MzkwMDIzMDExMTM2L2VhMTczNTA5ZXg5OS0xX3B1cnBsZWlubi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB575623b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> this press release</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purple Innovation, Inc. (NASDAQ: PRPL) ("Purpl=
e" or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D), a comfort innovation company known fo=
r creating the "World's First No Pressure=C2=AE Mattress," today announced =
that the Special Committee of its Board of Directors (the =E2=80=9CBoard=E2=
=80=9D) has declared a dividend of one new Proportional Representation Pref=
erred Linked Stock (=E2=80=9CPRPLS=E2=80=9D) for each 100 shares of Purple =
common stock (=E2=80=9CCommon Stock=E2=80=9D) owned by Purple=E2=80=99s sha=
reholders. Each PRPLS will vote together with the Common Stock in the elect=
ion of directors, and related matters, and carry 10,000 votes each.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Holders of PRPLS will be entitled to allocate =
their votes among the nominees in director elections on a cumulative basis.=
 PRPLS holders can allocate all, none, or a portion of their votes to each =
director nominee up for election at the Company=E2=80=99s meetings of share=
holders. As an example, shareholders who collectively own 30% of Purple=E2=
=80=99s Common Stock will be able to use the voting rights associated with =
their PRPLS to effectively elect approximately 30% of the members of the Bo=
ard.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe purpose of the PRPLS is to protec=
t all shareholders and treat them equally,=E2=80=9D said Paul J. Zepf, Purp=
le Innovation=E2=80=99s Chairman of the Board. =E2=80=9CPurple shareholders=
 will have the opportunity for proportional representation on the Purple Bo=
ard of Directors. By cumulating their PRPLS votes for certain director nomi=
nees, public shareholders can support the election of directors they believ=
e will act independently to represent the interests of all shareholders in =
the boardroom, roughly in proportion to their collective ownership in the C=
ompany.=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Prior to the issuance of the PRPLS, Coliseum m=
ight have been able to single-handedly nominate and elect all of the direct=
ors on the Board, including the five nominees Coliseum has selected.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With the issuance of PRPLS, all shareholders, =
including those not affiliated with Coliseum, will be able to cumulate thei=
r PRPLS votes on director candidates they feel will best represent the inte=
rests of all shareholders. This will help ensure that all shareholders rece=
ive ongoing independent representation on the Board. The PRPLS enable share=
holders who are not affiliated with Coliseum to choose and elect as many as=
 55% of the directors on the Purple Board.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Company is issuing one-one hundredth PRPLS=
 for each share of Common Stock held as of the close of business on Februar=
y 24, 2023. The PRPLS will trade with the Common Stock and any new issuance=
 of Common Stock will automatically include a proportionate number of PRPLS=
. The PRPLS are redeemable at any time by an affirmative vote of two-thirds=
 of the members of the Board.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ten thousand votes per PRPLS! I mean, each com=
mon share gets 1/100th of a PRPLS,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> so each common share gets 100 extra votes. The one normal vote per com=
mon share is not cumulative, but the 100 PRPLS votes are, so Purple has eff=
ectively switched to cumulative voting.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I dunno, seems fine? A lot of the time, when c=
ompanies try to fight off a big shareholder, they do it with things that=C2=
=A0<em>discriminate=C2=A0</em>against that shareholder: most classically a =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMTgvdHdpd=
HRlci1oYXMtYS1wb2lzb24tcGlsbC1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjE1JnV0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe95d1c2f" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  pois=
on pill</a> (basically threatening to give a ton of new stock to every shar=
eholder except the one you don=E2=80=99t like), though there is also the ti=
me that CBS Corp.=E2=80=99s board of directors tried to <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30562430.279853/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMTUvY2JzLXdhbnRzLXRvLWdldC1y=
aWQtb2YtYS1zaGFyZWhvbGRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMTUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa364648a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  issue a bunc=
h of new stock</a> to take away the super-voting rights of Shari Redstone, =
its controlling shareholder. Here, every shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0Coliseu=
m and otherwise =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets the same PRPLS and the same voting righ=
ts, but the board has changed how the votes get counted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mostly we just live in a golden age of blank-c=
heck preferred stock with weird voting rights and fun acronyms. I don=E2=80=
=99t think that a lot of companies will=C2=A0<em>copy=C2=A0</em>this idea, =
just because you need a really specific set of circumstances (pretty much: =
a single shareholder with more than about 35% of the stock and less than 50=
%, whom the board doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>like</em>) for this to make any =
sense. But if anyone does, will they use Purple=E2=80=99s PRPLS name? As a =
little tribute? Or will they have to come up with their own acronym?</p>
